result.execSummary:
The defendant Tanya M O'Neil was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling [Modifiers: as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).
  • Theft-Movable Property >$2500-$5000 [Modifiers: as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] case called at 2:09pm. 
Defendant Tanya M O'Neil in court, in custody, with Attorney Whitney Hagemann.   DA Susan Happ appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Attorney Hagemann clarifies that she had not been formally appointed by the Public Defender, so she has not read the original sentencing hearing transcript. On Count #10 the Court sentences Ms. O'Neil to 3 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of  1 year, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of  2 years.  This sentence is concurrent with the Sentence in Count #8.
The Court finds that the Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that the Defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives 427 days credit for time already served.

The Court orders as conditions of Extended Supervision:
--random drug screening
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with treatment recommendations as required by the Agent
--no possession of controlled substances without a valid doctor's prescription
--no possession of drug paraphernalia, including syringes, without a valid doctor's prescription 
--to undergo assessment, treatment, or counseling as required by the Agent
--no contact with Timothy Schultz except as approved by the Agent 
--no presence in any bars, taverns, liquors
--no consumption of alcohol 
--to comply with DNA sample provision upon demand

The Court orders entry of a civil judgment for unpaid court financial obligations and restitution as to all counts in this case--not only on Count #8 but also on the other Counts [Counts #10 and #12].

The Court indicates to the clerk that when the Judgment of Conviction is amended, the clerk is to make sure that-- as to Count #8--that the boxes are checked to show that the Court is finding Ms. O'Neil to be eligible for the programming [the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp" and the Substance Abuse Program] as to that Count #8.
